#include<stdio.h>
#include<string.h>
int main()
{
    char *str[]={"Progs","Do","Not","Die","They","Croak!"};
    printf("%d  %d",sizeof(str), strlen(str[0]));
    return 0;
}
///////////////////////////////////////////
1️⃣ Understanding the declaration
char *str[] = {"Progs","Do","Not","Die","They","Croak!"};

This means:

str → array of pointers to char

Number of elements = 6

Memory conceptually:

str[0] → "Progs"
str[1] → "Do"
str[2] → "Not"
str[3] → "Die"
str[4] → "They"
str[5] → "Croak!"

Each element is a pointer.

2️⃣ sizeof(str)

sizeof(str) gives the total size of the array of pointers, not the strings.

Formula:

sizeof(str) = number_of_elements × size_of_pointer

Number of elements = 6

Pointer size depends on system.

On 64-bit system
pointer size = 8 bytes
sizeof(str) = 6 × 8 = 48
On 32-bit system
pointer size = 4 bytes
sizeof(str) = 6 × 4 = 24
3️⃣ strlen(str[0])
str[0] → "Progs"

Characters:

P r o g s

Length = 5

strlen() does not count the null terminator \0.

So:

strlen("Progs") = 5
4️⃣ Final Output
On 64-bit system (most modern systems)
48  5
On 32-bit system
24  5
5️⃣ Memory Diagram
str (array of 6 pointers)
+-------+     +--------+
|str[0] |---->|"Progs" |
|str[1] |---->|"Do"    |
|str[2] |---->|"Not"   |
|str[3] |---->|"Die"   |
|str[4] |---->|"They"  |
|str[5] |---->|"Croak!"|
+-------+

Each pointer occupies 4 or 8 bytes, but the strings are stored elsewhere.

6️⃣ Important Interview Concepts

1️⃣ char *str[] → array of pointers
2️⃣ sizeof(array) gives total array memory
3️⃣ strlen() counts characters in a string
4️⃣ Pointer size affects sizeof() result
